# Boxel AI Website â€” Complete Architecture & Implementation Guide

> **Comprehensive guide** to building a multi-page marketing site with card-based architecture: navigation systems, section composition, brand integration, animated backgrounds, and the complete Boxel AI Website implementation using the `containsMany` section pattern.

---

## 1. Overview

This document provides a complete architectural blueprint for implementing the Boxel AI Website as a sophisticated card-based system. It covers:

- **Multi-page navigation** with active page highlighting and section jump menus
- **Site-wide configuration** through centralized Site and Page cards
- **Polymorphic section composition** using the `containsMany(PageSectionField)` pattern
- **Brand guide integration** with CSS variable APIs for logos and colors
- **Animated card compositions** (AnimatedGrid as background layers)
- **Orchestrator-to-section CSS contracts** for consistent spacing and layout
- **Complete section library** (Hero, Video, Three Modes, Stack, Skills, Catalog, Economy, CTA, Footer)
- **Example card linking** for interactive tiles and catalog items

The architecture supports **multiple page layouts** (Product, Docs, Pricing, Blog, Community) that share a common navigation component while maintaining independent content sections. Each layout declares its identity via `currentPageId`, enabling context-aware navigation with section dropdowns for pages that need them.

---

## 2. Architecture Overview

### 2.1 The Three-Layer Pattern

The architecture separates concerns across three distinct layers:

1. **Site Card** (Data Layer) â€” Central registry holding sitemap and all page references
2. **Layout Cards** (Orchestrator Layer) â€” Page-specific cards that compose sections (HomeLayoutCard, DocsLayoutCard)
3. **Navigation Component** (Presentation Layer) â€” Reusable component that receives active page as parameter

### 2.2 Why This Matters

This separation enables:
- **Single source of truth** for navigation across all pages
- **Independent page editing** without affecting site structure
- **Active page highlighting** based on context
- **Easy scaling** to add new pages (Pricing, About, etc.)
- **Clean component reuse** across different layouts

### 2.3 How It Works

```gts
// 1. Site card stores all pages and navigation data
export class Site extends CardDef {
  @field siteTitle = contains(StringField);
  @field pages = linksToMany(() => PageCard);
  @field ctaPrimaryText = contains(StringField);
}

// 2. Page card knows its metadata
export class PageCard extends CardDef {
  @field pageId = contains(StringField);      // "home" | "docs"
  @field pageLabel = contains(StringField);   // "Home" | "Documentation"
  @field pageUrl = contains(UrlField);        // "/" | "/docs"
  @field showInNav = contains(BooleanField);
  @field navOrder = contains(NumberField);
}

// 3. Layout cards link to Site and declare their pageId
export class HomeLayoutCard extends CardDef {
  @field site = linksTo(() => Site);              // Links to shared site config
  @field currentPageId = contains(StringField);   // "home" (identifies this page)
  @field sections = containsMany(PageSectionField);
}

export class DocsLayoutCard extends CardDef {
  @field site = linksTo(() => Site);              // Same site config
  @field currentPageId = contains(StringField);   // "docs" (different page ID)
  @field showSidebar = contains(BooleanField);
  @field sections = containsMany(PageSectionField);
}

// 4. Navigation component receives site + currentPageId
<SiteNavbar 
  @site={{@model.site}} 
  @currentPageId={{@model.currentPageId}} 
/>
```

### 2.4 Navigation Highlighting

The `SiteNavbar` component compares `currentPageId` to each page's `page
Id` to determine which link to highlight:

```gts
export class SiteNavbar extends Component<SiteNavbarSignature> {
  isActive = (pageId: string) => {
    return pageId === this.args.currentPageId;
  }

  <template>
    <nav class="site-navbar">
      {{#each this.sortedPages as |page|}}
        <a 
          href={{page.pageUrl}} 
          class="nav-link {{if (this.isActive page.pageId) 'active' ''}}"
        >
          {{page.pageLabel}}
        </a>
      {{/each}}
    </nav>

    <style scoped>
      .nav-link.active {
        font-weight: 600;
        color: var(--primary);
      }
    </style>
  </template>
}
```

### 2.5 Data Flow Diagram

```
Site Card (boxel-site.json)
  â”œâ”€ pages[0] â†’ Page Card (home-page.json)
  â”‚              â””â”€ pageId: "home"
  â”œâ”€ pages[1] â†’ Page Card (docs-page.json)
  â”‚              â””â”€ pageId: "docs"
  â””â”€ siteTitle, logos, CTAs

HomeLayoutCard (homepage.json)          DocsLayoutCard (docs-page.json)
  â”œâ”€ site â†’ [links to Site Card]          â”œâ”€ site â†’ [links to Site Card]
  â”œâ”€ currentPageId: "home"                 â”œâ”€ currentPageId: "docs"
  â””â”€ sections â†’ [Hero, Video, ...]        â””â”€ sections â†’ [DocsIntro, ...]

           â†“                                         â†“

     SiteNavbar                               SiteNavbar
  @site={{site}}                           @site={{site}}
  @currentPageId="home"                    @currentPageId="docs"

  Renders: Home | Docs                     Renders: Home | Docs
           ^^^^   (inactive)                        (inactive)  ^^^^  
```

### 2.6 Benefits

1. **Centralized Navigation Data** â€” All nav links, logos, and CTAs defined once in Site card
2. **Parameterized Component** â€” SiteNavbar receives state, doesn't own data
3. **Active State Management** â€” Each layout declares its identity via `currentPageId`
4. **Easy Extension** â€” Add new pages by creating PageCard instance and new layout card
5. **Clean Separation** â€” Data (Site) vs Presentation (SiteNavbar) vs Orchestration (Layouts)

---

## 3. Core Pattern

The architecture uses a **polymorphic section container** pattern where:

1. **Orchestrator Card** (`SiteLayoutCard`) contains navigation, sections array, and footer
2. **Section Field** (`PageSectionField`) wraps each content section with metadata
3. **Content Cards** extend a base class (`SectionCard`) and provide their own isolated templates
4. **Field Definitions** handle compound data within sections (tiles, items, links)

### The Key Insight

```gts
// Each section wraps a polymorphic content card
export class PageSectionField extends FieldDef {
  @field sectionId = contains(StringField);      // "001-hero"
  @field sectionLabel = contains(StringField);   // "Vision"
  @field content = linksTo(SectionCard);         // â† Polymorphic!
}

// Orchestrator holds all sections
export class SiteLayoutCard extends CardDef {
  @field sections = containsMany(PageSectionField);
}
```

This means each section (Hero, Video, Three Modes, etc.) is its own card instance that can be independently edited, while the `SiteLayoutCard` orchestrates their display order.

